<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="33" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1401,1643]" pageId="11" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1401,1427]" pageId="11" pageNumber="33">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Members of the species-group are characterized by the bright orange forewing colouration with a darker medial area and a distinct pattern. The male genitalia structure is reminiscent of that of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Benedek &amp; Volynkin &amp; Babics &amp; Saldaitis" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Moore" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[1154,1275,1437,1463]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Polymixis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albirena">
<emphasis box="[1154,1275,1437,1463]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="33">P. albirena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group (
<figureCitation box="[160,243,1473,1500]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–23" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1894,1918]" captionTargetBox="[171,1411,194,1859]" captionTargetId="figure-34@7.[159,1428,181,1869]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 21–23. Polymixis spp.: male genitalia. Depositories of the specimens dissected: 21 in BBT; 22 in ZFMK (photo by D. Stüning); 23 in HNHM (photo by Zs. Balint &amp; G. Katona)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5089293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5089293/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="33">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
) but differs by the asymmetrical clavi, the apically pointed dorsal costal protrusion, the markedly more elongate cucullus, the distally wider sacculus, and the less elongate left digitus which is not protruding beyond the ventral margin of the valva. The female genitalia of the species-group differ from those of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Benedek &amp; Volynkin &amp; Babics &amp; Saldaitis" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Moore" baseAuthorityYear="1881" box="[1211,1371,1545,1571]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Polymixis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albosignata">
<emphasis box="[1211,1371,1545,1571]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="33">P. albosignata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 30–35" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[217,1369,185,1899]" captionTargetId="figure-19@10.[205,1382,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 30–35. Polymixis spp.: female genitalia. Depositories of the specimens dissected: 30, 33–35 in BBT; 31 in ZFMK (photo by D. Stüning); 32 in HNHM (photo by Zs. Balint &amp; G. Katona)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5089303" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5089303/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="33">Figs 30, 31</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Benedek &amp; Volynkin &amp; Babics &amp; Saldaitis" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Moore" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[284,405,1581,1607]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Polymixis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="33" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albirena">
<emphasis box="[284,405,1581,1607]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="33">P. albirena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-groups (
<figureCitation box="[593,674,1581,1608]" captionStart="FIGURES 30–35" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[217,1369,185,1899]" captionTargetId="figure-19@10.[205,1382,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 30–35. Polymixis spp.: female genitalia. Depositories of the specimens dissected: 30, 33–35 in BBT; 31 in ZFMK (photo by D. Stüning); 32 in HNHM (photo by Zs. Balint &amp; G. Katona)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5089303" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5089303/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="33">Fig. 32</figureCitation>
) by the less elongate ductus bursae and the more weakly sclerotized appendix bursae.
</paragraph>
